---
import Content from '../../layouts/Content.astro'
import Heading from '../../components/Heading.astro'
import Article from '../../components/Article.astro'
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro'
import Sidebar from '../../layouts/Sidebar.astro'
import Header from '../../components/Header.astro'
import { SEO } from 'astro-seo'
import '../../styles/main.scss'

const siteUrl = Astro.site?.toString() || 'https://amandaliczner.ca'
---

<SEO
  title="Pathogen Risk to Bumble Bees Across Canada | Disease Spillover Research"
  description="Mapping pathogen spillover risk from managed bees to wild bumble bee populations across Canada. Conservation research identifying high-risk areas for disease transmission and bumble bee protection by Dr. Amanda Liczner."
  canonical={`${siteUrl}/experience/urban-gardens`}
  openGraph={{
    basic: {
      title: 'Pathogen Risk & Bumble Bee Conservation Across Canada',
      type: 'article',
      image: `${siteUrl}/pictures/urbangardens.jpg`,
      url: `${siteUrl}/experience/urban-gardens`,
    },
    optional: {
      description: 'Research mapping disease spillover risk from managed bees to wild bumble bees, identifying conservation priority areas at risk across Canada.',
      siteName: 'Dr. Amanda Liczner - Ecologist',
      locale: 'en_CA',
    },
    article: {
      authors: ['Dr. Amanda Liczner'],
      tags: ['bumble bees', 'pathogen spillover', 'disease transmission', 'conservation', 'managed bees', 'Canada'],
    },
    image: {
      url: `${siteUrl}/pictures/urbangardens.jpg`,
      secureUrl: `${siteUrl}/pictures/urbangardens.jpg`,
      alt: 'Bumble bee conservation research related to pathogen risk mapping',
      type: 'image/jpeg',
      width: 1200,
      height: 800,
    }
  }}
  twitter={{
    card: 'summary_large_image',
    site: '@amandaliczner',
    creator: '@amandaliczner',
    title: 'Pathogen Risk to Wild Bumble Bees Across Canada',
    description: 'Mapping disease spillover risk from managed bees to wild populations, identifying conservation hotspots.',
    image: `${siteUrl}/pictures/urbangardens.jpg`,
    imageAlt: 'Bumble bee pathogen research',
  }}
  extend={{
    meta: [
      { name: 'keywords', content: 'bumble bee pathogens, disease spillover, managed bees, wild bees, pathogen transmission, bumble bee conservation, Canada bee health, pollinator disease, conservation priority areas' },
      { name: 'author', content: 'Dr. Amanda Liczner' },
      { name: 'robots', content: 'index, follow' },
      { property: 'article:author', content: 'Dr. Amanda Liczner' },
      { property: 'article:section', content: 'Research' },
      { name: 'geo.region', content: 'CA' },
    ],
    link: [
      { rel: 'alternate', hreflang: 'en-ca', href: `${siteUrl}/experience/urban-gardens` },
      { rel: 'alternate', hreflang: 'en', href: `${siteUrl}/experience/urban-gardens` },
    ]
  }}
/>

<!-- ScholarlyArticle Structured Data -->
<script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'ScholarlyArticle',
  'headline': 'Pathogen Risk to Bumble Bees Across Canada',
  'description': 'Research mapping pathogen spillover risk from managed bees to wild bumble bee populations across Canada, identifying high-priority conservation areas at risk of disease transmission.',
  'author': {
    '@type': 'Person',
    'name': 'Dr. Amanda Liczner',
    'jobTitle': 'Ecologist and Conservation Biologist',
    'url': siteUrl
  },
  'about': ['Bumble Bees', 'Pathogen Spillover', 'Disease Transmission', 'Conservation Biology', 'Managed Bees', 'Wildlife Health'],
  'keywords': 'bumble bees, pathogens, disease spillover, managed bees, conservation, Canada, bee health',
  'url': `${siteUrl}/experience/urban-gardens`,
  'image': `${siteUrl}/pictures/urbangardens.jpg`,
  'inLanguage': 'en-CA',
  'spatialCoverage': {
    '@type': 'Place',
    'name': 'Canada'
  }
})} />

<!-- Breadcrumb Structured Data -->
<script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'BreadcrumbList',
  'itemListElement': [
    {
      '@type': 'ListItem',
      'position': 1,
      'name': 'Home',
      'item': siteUrl
    },
    {
      '@type': 'ListItem',
      'position': 2,
      'name': 'Experience',
      'item': `${siteUrl}/experience`
    },
    {
      '@type': 'ListItem',
      'position': 3,
      'name': 'Pathogen Risk Research',
      'item': `${siteUrl}/experience/urban-gardens`
    }
  ]
})} />
---

<style>
  li {
    margin-left: 5%;
    margin-bottom: 5px;
    list-style-type: number;
  }
</style>
<Layout title="Urban Gardens - Amanda Liczner">
  <Sidebar class="lg:hidden" />
  <Header />
  <Content>
    <Article>
      <Heading
        slot="header"
        level={1}
        gradient
        class="inline-block"
        text="Pathogen risk to bumble bees across Canada"
      />

      <div class="mx-auto overflow-hidden md:max-w-3xl my-4 md:text-xl">
        <div class="md:flex my-4 md:space-x-4">
          <div class="md:w-3/5">
            Bumble bees are facing many challenges, and one growing concern is
            the spread of diseases from managed bees to wild populations. While
            scientists have known about this risk for years, few studies have
            mapped out where the danger is highest. Our research looked at this
            issue across Canada, identifying areas where conservation efforts
            for bumble bees overlap with regions at risk of disease spillover
            from managed bees.
          </div>
          <div class="md:w-2/5 my-4">
            <img
              class="h-72 w-full object-cover md:h-full rounded-full"
              src="/pictures/urbangardens.jpg"
              alt="Pathogen research related to bumble bee conservation"
            />
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="md:flex md:space-x-4">
          <div class="my-4">
            We found that more than 15% of high-priority conservation areas for
            bumble bees are at risk, with hotspots in southwest Alberta,
            southern British Columbia, southern Ontario, and southern
            Quebec—places that also happen to be home to the richest diversity
            of bumble bee species. The risk isn’t limited to farms or cities;
            even natural areas could be affected.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="md:flex md:space-x-4">
          <div class="my-4">
            To help protect wild bumble bees, we need to adopt better management
            practices, such as screening managed bees for disease, improving
            colony care, treating infections, and setting up national monitoring
            and reporting programs. Our findings give conservation groups and
            policymakers the tools to focus their efforts where they’re needed
            most, helping to safeguard these essential pollinators and the
            ecosystems they support.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </Article>
  </Content>
</Layout>
